classified
information.

17:44.730 --> 17:48.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's basically a catalogue of
how the NSA
has stored data over the past
two decades.

17:48.968 --> 17:50.002 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He has got stuff in paper.

17:50.036 --> 17:51.304 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He has got stuff on C.D.s.

17:51.337 --> 17:52.305 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He has got stuff on thumb
drives.

17:52.338 --> 17:55.308 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He has got stuff.

17:55.341 --> 17:57.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It just tells a story, and it's
a little archive
of the NSA.

17:57.977 --> 18:00.413 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And what is
Martin's defense
for all this?

18:00.446 --> 18:01.547 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What does he say?

18:01.580 --> 18:05.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MATT APUZZO: Well, we haven't
heard a full
defense.

18:05.384 --> 18:10.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our understanding of what he's
told the FBI
is he acknowledges that he took
the stuff

18:10.489 --> 18:16.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and he wasn't supposed to take
it, but there
seems to be a little bit of,
well, I was taking

18:16.162 --> 18:23.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this stuff home to study it to
become better
at my job, to become a better
patriot, to

18:23.102 --> 18:25.638 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be a better NSA contractor.

18:25.671 --> 18:31.177 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Unlike somebody like Edward
Snowden, who had,
you know, a privacy, a
libertarian bent, what

18:31.210 --> 18:35.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we're hearing about Harold
Martin is that
he was very rah-rah for the NSA
and for the

18:35.781 --> 18:39.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
government's programs and
believed that he
was a patriot.

18:39.652 --> 18:44.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, has the
government indicated
at all what they think his
motive might be

18:44.490 --> 18:45.658 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for this?

18:45.691 --> 18:47.093 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why would he have these tools in
his house?

18:47.126 --> 18:49.095 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MATT APUZZO: No, it's a great
question.

18:49.128 --> 18:52.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And more so than why did he have
these tools
in the house, if he's been doing
it 20 years,

18:52.765 --> 18:57.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
why would he start now, like --
and why would
he start with documents?

18:57.636 --> 18:59.572 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These are questions that are at
the heart
of the case.

18:59.605 --> 19:05.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think if the government
knew that in
a really big way, we would have
seen it in

19:05.111 --> 19:06.045 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the court documents.

19:06.078 --> 19:08.180 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We might have seen it in court.

19:08.214 --> 19:11.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so what you're hearing now
is, I think,
a lot of federal investigators
scratching

19:11.617 --> 19:15.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their head and saying, we know
we have got
a big case here and we know
there's a lot

19:15.454 --> 19:17.223 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of smoke, but can we prove it?

19:17.256 --> 19:21.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Can we prove that -- can we link
him to these
leaked documents, can we link
him to some

19:21.527 --> 19:23.529 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
other -- to a foreign
intelligence service?

19:23.562 --> 19:26.832 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And so far, that hasn't
materialized in a
provable way.

19:26.866 --> 19:30.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: More broadly,
can we just
talk a little bit about how
damaging this

19:30.369 --> 19:32.271 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
might be for the NSA?

19:32.304 --> 19:37.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is the second instance
where an NSA contractor
has walked out the door with
truckloads of

19:37.309 --> 19:39.111 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
incredibly valuable data.

19:39.145 --> 19:41.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is the impact on the NSA
from this kind
of a thing?

19:41.714 --> 19:43.315 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MATT APUZZO: Sure.

19:43.349 --> 19:46.719 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think one of the things, the
damage assessment,
the risk assessment is going on.

19:46.752 --> 19:52.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the questions they
are going to
have to face is, if they can't
figure out

19:52.191 --> 19:57.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if any of the data has been
compromised, do
they have to assume that it's
all been compromised?

19:57.530 --> 20:00.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And does that mean you have to
start shutting
down programs or whatnot?

20:00.499 --> 20:05.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But from a practical standpoint,
yes, it really
just does boggle the mind that
you can, for

20:05.337 --> 20:12.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
20 years, just walk out of the
building with
papers and thumb drives and
C.D.s and whatnot.

20:12.778 --> 20:15.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It certainly does make you
wonder how that
happens.

20:16.015 --> 20:19.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you can bet that that's
going to be something
that they are going to be
looking awful hard

20:19.218 --> 20:20.953 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
at.

20:20.986 --> 20:24.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And after Edward Snowden, too,
that we're
still having this discussion, it
kind of does

20:24.223 --> 20:25.191 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
boggle the mind.

20:25.224 --> 20:26.592 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right.

20:26.625 --> 20:28.360 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a case we will obviously
keep watching
as it goes forward.

20:28.394 --> 20:31.597 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Matt Apuzzo of The New York
Times, thanks
so much.

20:31.630 --> 20:43.109 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MATT APUZZO: Thanks for having
me.

20:43.142 --> 20:47.880 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
