21:12.404 --> 21:14.273 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Right.

21:14.306 --> 21:16.642 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The first time,
Mark, of course
was after Wednesday night's
debate, the final

21:16.675 --> 21:18.944 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
debate between these
presidential candidates.

21:18.978 --> 21:21.280 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What has changed since then?

21:21.313 --> 21:26.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: I think the third
debate, Judy,
I think there was an awareness
Donald Trump

21:26.318 --> 21:28.187 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is not an unintelligent man.

21:28.220 --> 21:34.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he understood, I think, two
things after
the debates, A, that Hillary
Clinton had beaten

21:34.894 --> 21:36.428 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
him in three debates.

21:36.462 --> 21:37.796 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She was better prepared.

21:37.830 --> 21:40.432 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
She outflanked him tactically.

21:40.466 --> 21:45.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She got him to go for the bait
on things like
choked when meeting with the
president of

21:45.271 --> 21:47.006 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Mexico.

21:47.039 --> 21:50.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And also there has to be the
understanding
that this was -- because he was
trailing,

21:50.709 --> 21:55.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has been trailing in the polls,
this was the
last great chance where two
campaigns collide,

21:55.381 --> 22:00.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they're on the same stage, he
could challenge,
change the terms of the debate.

22:00.152 --> 22:01.921 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He didn't.

22:01.954 --> 22:09.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he, I think, almost as a
consolation,
has tried to divert the debate
that he's losing

22:09.929 --> 22:15.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to a discussion, I mean, a
reckless and dangerous
discussion, about the legitimacy
of the American

22:15.935 --> 22:19.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
elections, something that's
never been challenged
before by any major party
candidate.

22:19.705 --> 22:21.774 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Where do you see
things right
now, David?

22:21.807 --> 22:24.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes, I do think
there is an
acceptance, I don't know if in
Donald Trump's

22:24.944 --> 22:28.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
brain, but certainly in the
Republican Party,
about the fact that he's going
to lose, or

22:28.347 --> 22:29.615 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the likelihood that he's going
to lose.

22:29.648 --> 22:32.451 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the question becomes, how do
people react
to that?

22:32.484 --> 22:35.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Two weeks ago, I was in Idaho,
and I ran into
a guy who said, well, obviously
Trump is going

22:35.654 --> 22:38.357 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to win because everybody I know
is voting
for him.

22:38.390 --> 22:41.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I tried to persuade -- argue
with this
guy, well, if you look at the
polls, he is

22:41.227 --> 22:42.194 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
actually not leading.

22:42.228 --> 22:43.696 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And this guy just wouldn't
accept that.

22:43.729 --> 22:45.831 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That was not part of his lived
reality.

22:45.864 --> 22:49.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you got the sense a guy like
that, if
Trump does lose, will be very
angry and disbelieving

22:49.535 --> 22:52.938 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and may be sensitive to the idea
that the
election was rigged.

22:52.972 --> 22:55.040 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Yesterday, I was in Mississippi.

22:55.074 --> 22:57.810 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And there, there was a quietude,
a passivity.

22:57.843 --> 23:01.113 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't know all the stages of
grief, but
acceptance is one of them.

23:01.146 --> 23:04.383 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And there was a level of
acceptance in a lot
of the folks I spoke to there.

23:04.416 --> 23:09.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I suspect that the latter group
is the larger
part and that, even if he does
protest the

23:09.054 --> 23:15.160 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
election in some way, there will
be some acceptance
that he lost fair and square.

23:15.194 --> 23:19.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark, how much
fallout is there
over Trump's unwillingness to
say that he

23:19.898 --> 23:24.003 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will accept the results of the
election, whatever
they are?

23:24.036 --> 23:27.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Well, I think,
first of all,
Judy, it puts other Republican
candidates

23:27.339 --> 23:29.241 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in a terrible position.

23:29.275 --> 23:37.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, you have noticed the
parade, the cavalcade
of Republicans attesting to
their belief in

23:37.283 --> 23:43.188 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the ballot box, the belief in
legitimacy and
validity of American elections.

23:43.222 --> 23:44.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Republicans are on the ballot on
November
8.

23:44.957 --> 23:48.727 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're going to win or lose by
100 votes
or 200 votes in some cases.

23:48.761 --> 23:52.331 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do they want the legitimacy of
that election
tested?

23:52.364 --> 23:57.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think, in that sense --
but just enlarging
upon what David -- the point
David made, it's

23:57.136 --> 24:00.072 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not restricted to the Trump
people who don't
believe.

24:00.105 --> 24:04.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are Democrats who don't
believe that
-- there is a cleavage and a
divide in this

24:04.143 --> 24:06.345 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
country like I have never seen
before.

24:06.378 --> 24:11.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you're on the other side from
me, you're
not simply wrong or ill-informed
or mistaken.

24:11.750 --> 24:14.253 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We don't share the same country,
the same
values.

24:14.286 --> 24:16.889 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You may not be the same kind of
an American
I am.

24:16.922 --> 24:20.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it's really dangerous
and it's an
enormous challenge for the next
president.

24:20.926 --> 24:26.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, David, you're
seeing that
out there on the trail, if you
will, where

24:26.665 --> 24:28.634 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you have been traveling around
the country.

24:28.667 --> 24:34.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I want to ask you, though, about
Trump's continued,
I don't know -- how do you
describe the state

24:34.273 --> 24:35.507 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
he's in?

24:35.541 --> 24:37.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He goes to the Al Smith Dinner
in New York
City last night.

24:37.676 --> 24:42.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This gets a lot of coverage
today, where he
-- instead of doing the sort of
self-deprecating

24:42.681 --> 24:48.721 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
jokes that people traditionally
do, he really
continues to go hard after
Hillary Clinton.

24:48.754 --> 24:51.357 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Does it matter at this point
that he's still
angry?

24:51.390 --> 24:54.526 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Well, angry is
what he does.

24:54.560 --> 24:59.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have to say, I read all the
coverage, expecting
to be appalled by his speech and
cheered by

24:59.431 --> 25:00.399 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Clinton's.

25:00.432 --> 25:01.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I thought they were both pretty
bad.

25:01.467 --> 25:03.569 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I thought they were both a
little too harsh.

25:03.602 --> 25:06.271 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
His was worse, but hers wasn't
funny or particularly
well-delivered.

25:06.305 --> 25:11.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's going to be a dreary
couple of years
of comedy acts, no matter who is
elected.

25:11.377 --> 25:16.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I do think that his attacks, the
line that
she hates Catholics, is just
tone-deaf and

25:16.849 --> 25:22.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's just inner bitterness that
is coming
to the surface in unattractive
ways.

25:22.054 --> 25:25.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I do think, starting with
the -- not only
starting, but continuing with
the claim that

25:25.624 --> 25:31.196 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
he won't accept the --
automatically the results
of the election does
fundamentally undermine

25:31.230 --> 25:33.232 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the etiquette we have built up
in our society.

25:33.265 --> 25:38.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our system is not only based on
rules, but
a series of self-restraints that
we won't

25:38.103 --> 25:42.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be as barbaric as we could be in
competing
for power because we know if
we're all barbaric

25:42.741 --> 25:45.778 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as we could be, the whole
country and the
whole society falls apart.

25:45.811 --> 25:49.681 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And my critique with
conservatives who say,
well, I really hate the guy, but
I need to

25:49.715 --> 25:53.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
vote for him because of the
Supreme Court,
the problem is that the moral
foundation of

25:53.652 --> 25:57.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the society, the way we interact
with each
other is more fundamental than
the Supreme

25:57.222 --> 25:59.158 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Court.

25:59.191 --> 26:03.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if that gets polluted and
that gets destroyed
by somebody who's just
brutalistic and savage,

26:03.562 --> 26:06.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then it doesn't matter who's on
the Supreme
Court because we have lost our
country.

26:06.632 --> 26:10.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think their argument
that the Supreme
Court is worth it is basically
the wrong argument

26:11.003 --> 26:12.337 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
when he's behaving this way.

26:12.371 --> 26:14.072 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Pick up on that,
Mark.

26:14.106 --> 26:15.474 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Sure.

26:15.507 --> 26:18.677 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
No, the Al Smith Dinner, first
of all, it's
a marvelous occasion.

26:18.710 --> 26:21.113 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's really where people,
candidates do come.

26:21.146 --> 26:23.649 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, Judy, you have covered
enough campaigns.

26:23.682 --> 26:27.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the first things every
press secretary
assures you is, the boss has a
wonderful sense

26:27.219 --> 26:33.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
