too.

30:11.243 --> 30:15.947 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he said he was going to vote
for neither
of the candidates, just because
he was so

30:15.981 --> 30:19.885 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
appalled, until that Trump
reference to not
respecting the election results.

30:19.918 --> 30:24.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then he decided to go for
Clinton, because
he said, listen, this guy's got
to lose badly.

30:24.489 --> 30:26.692 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have got to at least defend
that principle.

30:26.725 --> 30:30.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I do think that what he
said sort of
over -- did overshadow
everything he said

30:30.328 --> 30:33.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the debate and will drive up
some of Clinton's
margins potentially.

30:33.865 --> 30:38.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: There is so much
talk in this
country about how divided the
country is still

30:38.770 --> 30:42.474 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to be, Mark, after this
election.

30:42.507 --> 30:46.812 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Is there anything these
candidates can do,
either the candidates at the top
of the ticket,

30:46.845 --> 30:52.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Paul Ryan, or any of the other
candidates
can do to begin to address that,
or do you

30:52.684 --> 30:55.287 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
just wait until the election is
over and hope
it works out?

30:55.320 --> 31:00.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: You hope that
there will be
a sense of resolution.

31:00.592 --> 31:07.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think Democrats ought to be
concerned, Judy,
that the party, in this
election, has become

31:07.432 --> 31:12.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
almost prideful about the
college-educated
vote that it's getting, the
support that Hillary

31:12.571 --> 31:15.407 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Clinton is getting against
Donald Trump.

31:15.440 --> 31:24.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, understandably, white
working-class voters
or working-class voters have
felt abandoned,

31:24.216 --> 31:29.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have felt, in many senses,
disparaged by the
political leadership of the
country.

31:29.387 --> 31:33.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they have been the core
historically of
the Democratic Party, whether
it's Norma Rae

31:33.258 --> 31:39.064 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or Joe Hill or the great stories
of fighting
for the underdog.

31:39.097 --> 31:44.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think the Democrats, I
would hope that
Hillary Clinton and the
Democratic leadership

31:44.569 --> 31:49.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wouldn't be quite as smug about
saying, oh,
we have got the
college-educated, aren't we

31:49.875 --> 31:55.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
something, and understand that
the anger and
the sense of outrage and hurt
that these people

31:55.881 --> 31:59.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are feeling, many of whom are
supporting Donald
Trump, is legitimate and real.

31:59.851 --> 32:05.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they feel abandoned by the
Democratic
Party, by Washington and
certainly hurt by

32:05.490 --> 32:07.425 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Wall Street.

32:07.459 --> 32:10.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, David, no
matter what the
outcome, the Democrats are due
for some soul-searching,

32:10.996 --> 32:12.430 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
along with the Republicans?

32:12.464 --> 32:14.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Well, everybody.

32:14.299 --> 32:19.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, I certainly hear a lot
of people say
that Trump not only incited some
bad things.

32:19.037 --> 32:20.739 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He also exposed some things.

32:20.772 --> 32:24.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He exposed pain in the country
that a lot
of us didn't have the full
extent of, some

32:24.409 --> 32:26.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the divisions and chasms in
the country.

32:26.845 --> 32:31.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so that's been an education
which Donald
Trump has given us, to his
credit.

32:31.850 --> 32:34.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, secondly -- and maybe it's
just what
people say to me, but I hear a
lot of desire

32:34.753 --> 32:40.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for a snap-back, that we have
had so much
vulgarity, so much throwing away
of any standards

32:40.592 --> 32:44.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of decency, that there has been
a lot of people
coming forward and say, no,
let's -- on matters

32:44.830 --> 32:50.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of how we talk to each other, on
matters how
we respect each other and relate
to each other,

32:50.135 --> 32:53.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
let's not only stop doing this,
let's snap
back and address the problems
that we have

32:53.972 --> 32:56.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all been suffering under during
this election
campaign.

32:56.441 --> 32:58.210 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Wouldn't that be
a welcome
thing?

32:58.243 --> 33:02.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Well, David, the
coarsening
of the culture didn't begin with
Donald Trump.

33:02.214 --> 33:06.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's accelerated it, but it did
not -- we
have coarsened our country over
the last generation.

33:06.918 --> 33:16.962 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark Shields,
David Brooks,
thank you both.

33:16.962 --> 33:25.937 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark Shields,
David Brooks,
thank you both.

33:25.971 --> 33:30.508 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Student debt has been a big
talking point
on the 2016 campaign trail.

33:30.542 --> 33:35.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hillary Clinton proposes making
tuition free
for many students at public
colleges.

33:35.647 --> 33:40.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Donald Trump would expand limits
on how much
borrowers have to pay back each
month.

33:40.518 --> 33:43.355 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But what about those already
holding debt?

33:43.388 --> 33:48.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We take a look as part of our
series How the
Deck Is Stacked, funded by the
Corporation

33:48.260 --> 33:52.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for Public Broadcasting, in
partnership with
"Frontline" and Marketplace.

33:52.731 --> 33:56.668 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Marketplace's Lizzie O'Leary has
the first
of two stories.

33:56.701 --> 34:00.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LIZZIE O'LEARY, Marketplace: If
everything
had gone according to plan,
Chris Savelle

34:00.672 --> 34:05.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would be on Wall Street right
now, not biking
through downtown Detroit in a
free weekly

34:05.277 --> 34:06.611 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
community ride.

34:06.645 --> 34:11.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Savelle, who is 31, graduated
into the teeth
of the recession.

34:11.349 --> 34:15.287 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's got $100,000 in student
loan debt on
his mind.

34:15.320 --> 34:17.122 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What does $100,000 feel like?

34:17.155 --> 34:20.258 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHRIS SAVELLE, Owes Student
Debt: It sucks.

34:20.292 --> 34:23.628 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: Jessica Love
Jordan is in
a similar situation.

34:23.662 --> 34:28.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She started college late and is
now working
on finishing her master's in
addiction counseling.

34:28.934 --> 34:31.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She juggles school, work and
being a single
parent.

34:32.003 --> 34:33.838 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sometimes, the debt feels too
much.

34:33.872 --> 34:36.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JESSICA LOVE JORDAN, Owes
Student Debt: Now
and again, when I look at the
statement, and

34:36.074 --> 34:38.610 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see how much I actually have to
pay back,
it's almost suffocating.

34:38.643 --> 34:44.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have those fleeing thoughts,
you know what,
let me just stop now, and go
work, so I can

34:44.082 --> 34:46.117 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be able to live later on in
life.

34:46.151 --> 34:51.423 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: When she
graduates, she can
expect to make about $33,000
annually as an

34:51.456 --> 34:52.424 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
addiction counselor.

34:52.457 --> 34:55.393 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Her debt will be about $90,000.

34:55.427 --> 35:00.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The median student debt is much
lower than
Savelle or Love Jordan's, about
$27,000.

35:00.699 --> 35:05.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But their experiences are
similar to those
of many students who attended
state universities

35:05.971 --> 35:10.208 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at a time when their budgets
were being cut,
and as the great recession hit.

35:10.241 --> 35:15.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The money for school had to come
from somewhere,
in most cases, students.

35:15.380 --> 35:17.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Where did you think you would be
in your life
at 31?

35:17.949 --> 35:24.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS SAVELLE: Go work for an
investment firm
or hedge fund, Chicago, New
York, something

35:24.556 --> 35:26.291 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
like that.

35:26.324 --> 35:30.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: But when Savelle
graduated
in 2008, the best job he could
find was at

35:30.195 --> 35:31.596 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a local Wal-Mart.

35:31.629 --> 35:33.098 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He's recovered somewhat now.

35:33.131 --> 35:37.302 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He works as a supply chain
engineer, and supports
his mother and sister.

35:37.335 --> 35:41.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Temple University Professor Sara
Goldrick-Rab
has been researching the rising
price of college

35:41.640 --> 35:43.375 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for years.

35:43.408 --> 35:48.813 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How has the aid picture changed
as median
incomes have stagnated, really,
for the last

35:48.847 --> 35:50.615 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
20 years?

35:50.648 --> 35:52.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SARA GOLDRICK-RAB, Temple
University: The
sticker price on a per student
basis has gone

35:52.384 --> 35:57.989 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up a lot, while the amount of
financial aid
on a per student basis has gone
down.

35:58.023 --> 36:03.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the result is that the net
price, the
amount that the families
actually pay out

36:03.094 --> 36:06.498 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of their pocket, is rising, and
it's rising
fairly rapidly.

36:06.531 --> 36:09.734 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: More than 40
million Americans
have student loan debt.

36:09.768 --> 36:13.705 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The total amount is around $1.3
trillion.

36:13.738 --> 36:18.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Even so, there are experts like
Sandy Baum,
who studies student debt at the
Urban Institute,

36:18.476 --> 36:20.678 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and says only certain people are
being hurt.

36:20.712 --> 36:25.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SANDY BAUM, Urban Institute:
Student debt
is a crisis for some people, but
student debt

36:25.183 --> 36:32.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is not the generalized crisis
that the common
discourse would make it appear.

36:32.057 --> 36:36.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yes, people are paying more of
their incomes
for a college education, but
still it's worth

36:36.995 --> 36:38.496 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it for most people.

36:38.530 --> 36:41.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It's still a very good
investment for most
people, but not for everyone.

36:41.666 --> 36:46.671 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: Sara
Goldrick-Rab says far
too many people are being
saddled with substantial

36:46.704 --> 36:47.705 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
debt.

36:47.739 --> 36:50.842 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You wrote that debt is a
symptom, not the
disease.

36:50.875 --> 36:53.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It sounds like you think the
disease is the
high price.

36:53.978 --> 36:55.747 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SARA GOLDRICK-RAB: The disease
is the price.

36:55.780 --> 36:59.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we have a problem, where
people are being
priced out of college, and in
their effort

36:59.751 --> 37:04.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to not be priced out, they're
taking on debt
that, frankly, they're going to
have real

37:04.055 --> 37:05.023 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
trouble repaying.

37:05.056 --> 37:07.525 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: People like
Jordan Hoeft.

37:07.559 --> 37:10.495 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's been trying to get a more
manageable
payment plan.

37:10.528 --> 37:13.164 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He studied film, but couldn't
get a job in
